ce:section.ce:para:
It has been widely proved that CDs can interact with some metal cations (e.g. Hg2+, Fe3+) to quench the fluorescence [10,33–35]. As a consequence, the influence of common metal cations (Ag+, Zn2+, Na+, Mn2+, Co2+, Mg2+, Ba2+, K+, Ca2+, Cr3+, Ni2+, Al3+, Fe3+) on fluorescence of CQD102 and CQD106 is evaluated and shown in Fig. 5
                        a and b. Among these thirteen metal cations, Co2+, Cr3+ and Fe3+ ions display apparent quenching ability for CQD102 and CQD106. Furthermore, the fluorescence of CQD102 and CQD106 is nearly completely quenched by Fe3+ ions, suggesting that the two N-CDs have high selectivity towards Fe3+ ions. The effects of Fe3+ concentration on fluorescence quenching of the two N-CDs are presented in Fig. 5c and d. It can be also seen clearly that the relative PL intensity at around 423 nm gradually decreases with the increase of Fe3+ concentration. The data-fitting results reveal that there are good linear relationships between relative PL intensity and Fe3+ concentration in the range from 5 to 100 μM. The limit of detection (LOD) of CQD102 is calculated to be 0.482 μM base on the equation 3δ/K (δ is the standard deviation of eight blank signals and K is the slope of the calibration line), which is comparable to those values in literature (Table 2
                        ). The fluorescence quenching mechanism of Fe3+ ions towards CQD102 and CQD106 might be attributed to the non-radiative electron-transfer from the excited states to the d-orbit of Fe3+ ions (Fig. 3).
